<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="440" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,599,1922]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,887,914]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known so far only from eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[731,796,888,914]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Sicily</collectingRegion>
and the 
<collectingRegion box="[896,961,888,914]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Sicily</collectingRegion>
Strait (
<figureCitation box="[1046,1131,888,914]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1496,1521]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,958,1468]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,955,1471]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 13. Distribution based on the material examined and checked literature data. Red dots, Alvania scuderii Villari, 2017. Light-blue dots, Alvania pizzinii n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773007" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773007/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Living on Messina rocky bottom amidst algae, in 
<quantity box="[422,493,924,950]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" unit="m" value="5.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="2.0">2–8 m</quantity>
depth (eastern 
<collectingRegion box="[666,736,924,951]" country="Italy" name="Sicilia" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Sicily</collectingRegion>
); empty shells in 
<quantity box="[933,1032,923,950]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.6" metricValueMax="5.2" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" unit="m" value="36.0" valueMax="52.0" valueMin="20.0">20–52 m</quantity>
depth (see also https://www.naturamediterraneo.com/forum/topic.asp?TOPIC_ID=26442—accessed 
<date box="[897,1115,960,986]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" value="2017-12-13">13 december 2017</date>
, as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[1163,1337,960,986]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[1163,1337,960,986]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Alvania scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Found sympatric with 
<emphasis box="[326,579,996,1022]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[326,433,996,1022]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scabra">A. scabra</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Granata-Grillo" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[441,579,996,1022]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sororcula">A. sororcula</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Amati &amp; Appolloni &amp; Giulio &amp; Scuderi &amp; Smriglio &amp; Oliverio, 2020" authorityName="Amati &amp; Appolloni &amp; Giulio &amp; Scuderi &amp; Smriglio &amp; Oliverio" authorityYear="2020" box="[634,747,996,1022]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pizzinii" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[634,747,996,1022]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">A. pizzinii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[754,817,996,1022]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[754,817,996,1022]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
At Messina 
<emphasis box="[959,1219,996,1022]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[959,1069,996,1022]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scabra">A. scabra</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Granata-Grillo" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[1080,1219,996,1022]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sororcula">A. sororcula</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Villari" authorityYear="2017" box="[1273,1395,996,1022]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scuderii">
<emphasis box="[1273,1395,996,1022]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">A. scuderii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are syntopic in summer (DS, unpublished), with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Philippi" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[664,772,1032,1058]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[664,772,1032,1058]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">A. scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
more abundant, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Granata-Grillo" baseAuthorityYear="1877" box="[1014,1153,1032,1058]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis box="[1014,1153,1032,1058]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">A. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Villari" authorityYear="2017" box="[1210,1333,1032,1058]" class="Gastropoda" family="Rissoidae" genus="Alvania" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="scuderii">
<emphasis box="[1210,1333,1032,1058]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">A. scuderii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
showing slightly deeper depth ranges.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="440" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,599,1922]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1103,1130]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Description</emphasis>
(data for the 
<typeStatus box="[494,592,1104,1130]" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">holotype</typeStatus>
in parentheses). Shell (
<figureCitation box="[861,944,1104,1130]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1950,1975]" captionTargetBox="[265,1322,181,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[265,1322,181,1925]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 11. Alvania scuderii Villari, 2017. A–C. Linosa Is. 35 m depth (Italy), height 1.69 mm (CS-PM). D–F. same locality (Italy), height 1.8 mm (CS-PM). G–I. same locality (Italy), height 1.82 mm (CS-PM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773003" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773003/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Figs 11</figureCitation>
A–I; 17A–C) small for the genus, 1.55–2.1 (
<quantity box="[159,249,1140,1166]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
) mm, width 0.916–1.18 (1.18) mm, ratio H/W 1.69–1.78 (1.78), ovate-conic. Protoconch (
<figureCitation box="[1287,1428,1140,1166]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1791,1816]" captionTargetBox="[214,1373,181,1765]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[214,1373,181,1765]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 17. Alvania spp. (SEM). A–C. Alvania scuderii Villari, 2017, Linosa Is. 35 m depth (Italy), height 1.69 mm (CS-PM). A. Shell. B. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. C. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture, same specimen. D–F. Alvania pizzinii n. sp. holotype, MNHN IM-2000-33933, height 2.3 mm, Levanzo Is. (Italy). D. Shell. E. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. F. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture and of the subsutural ramp, same specimen. G–I. Alvania grancanariensis Segers, 1999, Maspalomas, Gran Canaria, Canary Islands (Spain) height 1.85 mm (JT, JDO). G. Shell. H. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. I. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture, same specimen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773015/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Figs 17B, C</figureCitation>
) paucispiral with nucleus moderately intorted, of 1.2–1.3 (1.3) whorls, height 
<geoCoordinate box="[1006,1069,1175,1201]" degrees="0.262" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="0.262">0.262</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1068,1146,1175,1201]" degrees="0.320" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="-0.32">–0.320</geoCoordinate>
(?) mm; nucleus diameter (d) 
<geoCoordinate box="[190,253,1212,1238]" degrees="0.100" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="0.1">0.100</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[253,330,1212,1238]" degrees="0.120" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="-0.12">–0.120</geoCoordinate>
(?) mm, first half whorl diameter (Do) 
<geoCoordinate box="[764,827,1211,1238]" degrees="0.157" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="0.157">0.157</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[827,904,1211,1238]" degrees="0.205" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="-0.205">–0.205</geoCoordinate>
(?) mm, maximum diameter (DM) 
<geoCoordinate box="[1296,1358,1211,1238]" degrees="0.295" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="0.295">0.295</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[1358,1436,1211,1238]" degrees="0.312" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="25" pageNumber="440" precision="55" value="-0.312">–0.312</geoCoordinate>
(?) mm, sculpture of parallel rows of microtubercles of different shapes, sometimes fused (
<figureCitation box="[1199,1344,1248,1274]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1791,1816]" captionTargetBox="[214,1373,181,1765]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[214,1373,181,1765]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 17. Alvania spp. (SEM). A–C. Alvania scuderii Villari, 2017, Linosa Is. 35 m depth (Italy), height 1.69 mm (CS-PM). A. Shell. B. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. C. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture, same specimen. D–F. Alvania pizzinii n. sp. holotype, MNHN IM-2000-33933, height 2.3 mm, Levanzo Is. (Italy). D. Shell. E. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. F. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture and of the subsutural ramp, same specimen. G–I. Alvania grancanariensis Segers, 1999, Maspalomas, Gran Canaria, Canary Islands (Spain) height 1.85 mm (JT, JDO). G. Shell. H. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. I. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture, same specimen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773015/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Figs 17B, C</figureCitation>
). Protoconch-teleoconch boundary well marked. Teleoconch of 2.9–3.4 (3.3) convex whorls, with suture impressed. Axial sculpture on the last whorl of 15–18 (?) slightly prosocline and sinuous ribs, plus the labial varix, narrower than the interspaces and interrupted at the base. Spiral sculpture same strength as axial, of almost equidistant cords, 8 (8) on the last whorl, with 4 (4) above the aperture and 4 (4) slightly thicker on the base. Cords II and IV starting immediately after the protoconch-teleoconch boundary; cord I appearing at 1.2–1.5 whorls (remaining thinner than others), cord III starting after 1.5–1.8 whorls (Table VII). Small, rounded tubercles at the intersections; interspaces quadrangular. Microsculpture of weak growth lines and spiral threads overall (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1145,1500,1526]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1791,1816]" captionTargetBox="[214,1373,181,1765]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[214,1373,181,1765]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 17. Alvania spp. (SEM). A–C. Alvania scuderii Villari, 2017, Linosa Is. 35 m depth (Italy), height 1.69 mm (CS-PM). A. Shell. B. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. C. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture, same specimen. D–F. Alvania pizzinii n. sp. holotype, MNHN IM-2000-33933, height 2.3 mm, Levanzo Is. (Italy). D. Shell. E. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. F. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture and of the subsutural ramp, same specimen. G–I. Alvania grancanariensis Segers, 1999, Maspalomas, Gran Canaria, Canary Islands (Spain) height 1.85 mm (JT, JDO). G. Shell. H. Detail of the protoconch microsculpture, same specimen. I. Detail of the teleoconch microsculpture, same specimen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773015/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Fig. 17B</figureCitation>
). Umbilical chink absent. Aperture pyriform, large, rounded ovate anteriorly, height 0.65–0.85 (0.85) mm, H/Ha ratio 2.36–2.61 (2.47), peristome continuous, outer varix modest, internally smooth. Background colouration brownish, with dark brown spiral cords, aperture and columella lighter. Operculum thin, paucispiral, with eccentric nucleus (see alsoVillari 2017). Soft parts (
<figureCitation box="[279,427,1644,1670]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1801,1826]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,194,1766]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[151,1436,181,1776]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Alvania spp. drawing of external soft parts. A, B. Alvania scabra (Philippi, 1844), S. Giovanni Li Cuti, Catania, Sicily, 4 m depth (DS). C, D. Alvania scabra (Philippi, 1844), Los Escullos, Cabo de Gata, Spain, (AN29. MNHN), redrawn after a sketch by Serge Gofas (Malaga). E, F. Alvania sororcula (Granata-Grillo, 1877), S. Raineri, “Degassifica”, Messina, Sicily, 2–4 m depth (DS). G, H. Alvania scuderii Villari, 2017, Ganzirri, Messina, Sicily, 4–5 m depth (MZB)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773017/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="440">Figs 18G, H</figureCitation>
): semi-transparent whitish background with grey/dark-grey areas on both sides of body, darker on opercular area, extending at edge of sole of foot. Pale brownish median area on snout. Yellow speckles on snout, merged in short stripes on head behind and in front of eyes, forming lines along cephalic tentacles, on foot and opercular area, on propodium, and a yellow π figure under the operculum; two whitish granular masses near eyes, scattered white speckles on cephalic tentacles; 4 metapodial tentacles. (See also Villari, 2017).
</paragraph>
